{"title_page": "Arshad Chaudhry", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistani field hockey player}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name             = Arshad Chaudhry\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = <!--if different-->\n| birth_date       = April 10, 1950\n| birth_place      = [[Faisalabad]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2015|6|11|1950|4|10}}<ref name=\"Obituary\"/>\n| death_place      = [[Lahore]], Pakistan\n| headercolor      = lightsteelblue\n| show-medals      = yes\n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[field hockey]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{PAK}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[1976 Summer Olympics|1976 Montreal]] | [[Field hockey at the 1976 Summer Olympics|Team competition]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Asian Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[1974 Asian Games|1974 Tehran]] | [[Field hockey at the 1974 Asian Games|Team competition]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Arshad Ali Chaudhry''' (April 10, 1950 \u2013 June 11, 2015) was an international field hockey player from [[Pakistan]]. He is son of Chaudhry Sadique Salar, the nephew of [[Chaudhry Ghulam Rasool]], and cousin of [[Akhtar Rasool]].<ref>Pakistan Economist, 1972, p ix, Pakistan</ref> Chaudhry was born in [[Faislabad]] (formerly [[Faisalabad]]) District of [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]], Pakistan. He earned his B.A. from Government College [[Faislabad]] where he was also the captain of college hockey team. He got an M.A. in History from [[University of the Punjab|Punjab University]], Lahore in 1973. In 1975 he was selected Assistant Manager in PIA.\n\nChaudhry was selected for the Punjab University Hockey team in 1971 for the Inter-Varsity Hockey Championship held at [[Karachi]].<ref>R\u0101v\u012b, 1971, p 92, Government College (Lahore, Pakistan).</ref> The team won the Inter-Varsity Championship the following year. Chaudhry remained an active hockey international player in the Pakistani national team from 1971 through 1976<ref name=\"phf\" /> and played as right half-back. He represented Pakistan in over 33 national and international matches.<ref name=\"phf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.phf.com.pk/int_record.php |title=Pakistan Hockey Federation |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030206033223/http://www.phf.com.pk/int_record.php |archivedate=February 6, 2003|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> He represented Pakistani Men's hockey team which participated in the 1975 third World Cup Hockey, held at [[Kualalumpur]] and won the [[Silver Medal]].{{cn|date=November 2013}} In 1976 he participated in the [[1976 Summer Olympics]] held at [[Montreal]] and won a bronze medal.<ref>http://www.quadrodemedalhas.com/en/olympic-games/summer-olympic-games-field-hockey.htm.</ref><ref>The complete book of the Olympics, 1984, p 277, David Wallechinsky \u2013 Sports & Recreation.</ref> He retired from active hockey after the [[Montreal]] [[Summer Olympic Games|Olympics]] in 1976 and died in June 2015 at the age of 65.<ref name=\"Obituary\">[http://www.dawn.com/news/1187739 Arshad Chaudhry's obituary] Dawn (newspaper), Published 12 June 2015, Retrieved 5 July 2018</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ch/arshad-ali-chaudry-1.html |title=Arshad Ali Chaudhry}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chaudhry, Arshad}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Pakistani male field hockey players]]\n[[Category:Olympic field hockey players of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in field hockey]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Asian Games medalists in field hockey]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 1974 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games gold medalists for Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1974 Asian Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pakistani field hockey player}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name             = Arshad Chaudhry\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = <!--if different-->\n| birth_date       = April 10, 1950\n| birth_place      = [[Faisalabad]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2015|6|11|1950|4|10}}<ref name=\"Obituary\"/>\n| death_place      = [[Lahore]], Pakistan\n| headercolor      = lightsteelblue\n| show-medals      = yes\n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[field hockey]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{PAK}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[1976 Summer Olympics|1976 Montreal]] | [[Field hockey at the 1976 Summer Olympics|Team competition]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Asian Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[1974 Asian Games|1974 Tehran]] | [[Field hockey at the 1974 Asian Games|Team competition]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Arshad Ali Chaudhry''' (April 10, 1950 \u2013 June 11, 2015) was an international field hockey player from [[Pakistan]]. He is son of Chaudhry Sadique Salar, the nephew of [[Chaudhry Ghulam Rasool]], and cousin of [[Akhtar Rasool]].<ref>Pakistan Economist, 1972, p ix, Pakistan</ref> Chaudhry was born in [[Faislabad]] (formerly [[Faisalabad]]) District of [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]], Pakistan. He earned his B.A. from Government College [[Faislabad]] where he was also the captain of college hockey team. He got an M.A. in History from [[University of the Punjab|Punjab University]], Lahore in 1973. In 1975 he was selected Assistant Manager in PIA.\n\nChaudhry was selected for the Punjab University Hockey team in 1971 for the Inter-Varsity Hockey Championship held at [[Karachi]].<ref>R\u0101v\u012b, 1971, p 92, Government College (Lahore, Pakistan).</ref> The team won the Inter-Varsity Championship the following year. Chaudhry remained an active hockey international player in the Pakistani national team from 1971 through 1976<ref name=\"phf\" /> and played as right half-back. He represented Pakistan in over 33 national and international matches.<ref name=\"phf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.phf.com.pk/int_record.php |title=Pakistan Hockey Federation |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030206033223/http://www.phf.com.pk/int_record.php |archivedate=February 6, 2003|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> He represented Pakistani Men's hockey team  which participated in the 1975 third World Cup Hockey, held at  [[Kualalumpur]] and won the [[Silver]] Medal.{{cn|date=November 2013}} In 1976 he participated in the [[1976 Summer Olympics]] held at [[Montreal]] and won a bronze medal.<ref>http://www.quadrodemedalhas.com/en/olympic-games/summer-olympic-games-field-hockey.htm.</ref><ref>The complete book of the Olympics, 1984, p 277, David Wallechinsky \u2013 Sports & Recreation.</ref> He retired from active hockey after the [[Montreal]] [[Summer Olympic Games|Olympics]] in 1976 and died in June 2015 at the age of 65.<ref name=\"Obituary\">[http://www.dawn.com/news/1187739 Arshad Chaudhry's obituary] Dawn (newspaper), Published 12 June 2015, Retrieved 5 July 2018</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ch/arshad-ali-chaudry-1.html |title=Arshad Ali Chaudhry}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chaudhry, Arshad}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Pakistani male field hockey players]]\n[[Category:Olympic field hockey players of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in field hockey]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Asian Games medalists in field hockey]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 1974 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games gold medalists for Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1974 Asian Games]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:bad link repair, replaced:Silver\u2192Silver Medal", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arshad_Chaudhry"}
{"title_page": "List of NRL Grand finals", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}There have been 21 [[National Rugby League|NRL]] Premierships and 112 overall, including the competition's predecessors ([[New South Wales Rugby League premiership|NSWRL]], [[Australian Rugby League|ARL]] and [[Super League (Australia)|Super League]]). This is a list of all the grand finals that were played to decide those premierships.\n\nThe premierships not decided by a grand final were determined by league ladder position. These years were [[1909 NSWRFL season|1909]], [[1912 NSWRFL season|1912]], [[1913 NSWRFL season|1913]], [[1914 NSWRFL season|1914]], [[1915 NSWRFL season|1915]], [[1917 NSWRFL season|1917]], [[1918 NSWRFL season|1918]], [[1919 NSWRFL season|1919]], [[1920 NSWRFL season|1920]], [[1921 NSWRFL season|1921]], [[1925 NSWRFL season|1925]] and [[1937 NSWRFL season|1937]].\n\nSince 1954 the grand final was officially sanctioned as the only way to determine the premiership,<ref>{{cite news|last=Keeble|first=Brett|title=Sea Eagles return to NRL's top perch|url=http://www.theherald.com.au/story/488759/sea-eagles-return-to-nrls-top-perch/|accessdate=4 November 2012|newspaper=[[Newcastle Herald]]|date=5 October 2008}}</ref> but it had been commonplace for decades before that.\n\n== List ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! width=\"3%\" |Season\n! width=\"15%\" |Premiers\n! width=\"5%\" |Score\n! width=\"15%\" |Runners-up\n! width=\"10%\" |Referee(s)\n! width=\"15%\" |Venue\n! width=\"7%\" |Attendance\n! width=\"10%\" |Date\n|-\n! colspan=\"8\" |[[New South Wales Rugby League]]\n|-\n|[[1908 NSWRFL season|1908]]\n|{{leagueicon|South Sydney|size=16}} South Sydney\n|14 \u2013 12\n|{{Leagueicon|Sydney|16}} Eastern Suburbs\n|C. Hutchison\n|[[Sydney Showground (Moore Park)|RAS Showground]]\n[[Sydney]]\n|4,000\n|29 August 1908\n|-\n|[[1909 NSWRFL season|1