{"title_page": "Hussain Shah", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistani boxer}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name           = Hussain Shah\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| realname       = Syed Hussain Shah\n| nickname       = \n| weight         = [[Middleweight#boxing|middleweight]]\n| height         = <!-- \"X ft Y in\" or \"X cm\" (conversions are automatic) -->\n| reach          = <!-- \"X in\" or \"X cm\" (conversions are automatic) -->\n| nationality    = [[Pakistan]]i\n| birth_name     = Syed Hussain Shah\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1964|08|14}}\n| birth_place    = [[Lyari]], [[Karachi]], Pakistan\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| style          = \n| total          = 4\n| wins           = 3\n| KO             = \n| losses         = 1\n| draws          = \n| no contests    = \n| website        = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Boxing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{PAK}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Boxing at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Seoul]] | [[Boxing at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Middleweight|Middleweight]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Boxing at the South Asian Games|South Asian Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1984 South Asian Games|1984 Kathmandu]] | [[Boxing at the 1984 South Asian Games \u2013 Middleweight|Middleweight]]}}\n| show-medals    = yes\n| embed          = \n}}\n\n'''Syed Hussain Shah''' ({{lang-ur|\u0633\u064a\u062f \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646 \u0634\u0627\u0647}}) (born August 14, 1964) is a retired [[Pakistan]]i [[boxing|boxer]] from [[Lyari]], [[Karachi]] [[Pakistan]], who won the bronze medal in the Middleweight division (71\u201375&nbsp;kg) at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]] in [[Seoul]], South Korea. This was the country's first ever Olympic boxing medal.<ref name=\"news\">[http://www.thenews.com.pk/article-155105-Pakistans-Shah-Hussain-reaches-mens-judo-finals- Pakistan's Shah Hussain reaches men's judo final] 26 July 2014 Retrieved 26 July 2014</ref> He remains the only Pakistani sportsperson to win an individual medal at the [[Olympic Games]] in the last fifty-plus years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Must watch: An unsung Pakistani hero comes to life in film 'Shah'|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1191855|accessdate=17 February 2016|work=[[DAWN (newspaper)|DAWN]]|date=2 July 2015}}</ref> Only other Pakistani to ever win an individual Olympic medal is the wrestler [[Muhammad Bashir]], who won a bronze medal at the [[1960 Summer Olympics]].\n\n==Early life==\nShah was born in Lyari, Karachi. As a child Shah lived used to live on streets due to being homeless, he used to work as labor to earn money. Shah trained himself for boxing on streets using garbage bags as a replacement for [[punching bag]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/120097/hussain-shah-the-boxing-icon-who-won-olympic-medal-for-pakistan-in-1988/ |title=Hussain Shah \u2013 The boxing icon who won Olympic medal for Pakistan in 1988 |publisher=Daily Times |date=August 20, 2017 |website=dailytimes.com.pk |access-date=October 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShah won his first gold medal at [[1984 South Asian Games]] in [[Dhaka]], along with Asghar Ali, Ilyas Ahmed and Muhammad Yousaf.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sports.gov.pk/Participation/1st_SAF_Games.htm |title=I SAF Games |publisher=Pakistan Sports Board |website=sports.gov.pk |access-date=October 14, 2018}}</ref> At the [[1987 South Asian Games|1987 edition]] of the Games in [[Kolkata]], he was adjudged the 'best boxer'.<ref>{{cite newspaper |last1=Nair |first1=Avinash |title=Shah stops clean sweep |newspaper=The Indian Express |date=25 November 1987 |page=6}}</ref>\n\nAt the 1988 Olympics he shared the podium with [[Kenya]]'s [[Chris Sande]]. He was Pakistan's first boxer to win any medal in olympic boxing. In 1989, [[Lyari Town|Lyari]] born boxer received [[Sitara-i-Imtiaz]] medal from [[Government of Pakistan]].\n\nShah, who has also to his credit five gold in the South Asian Games history, remained the best boxer of Asia from 1980 to 1988, a rare prominence achieved by any Pakistani pugilist so far.\n\nHe later moved to Japan, where his son [[Shah Hussain Shah]] learned judo and went on to represent Pakistan at the international level.<ref>http://www.thenational.ae/sport/asian-games/shah-hussain-pakistans-young-japan-raised-judo-star-hopes-for-medal-repeat-at-asian-games</ref><ref>http://www.dawn.com/news/1122147</ref>\n\n==Films==\nA biopic called ''[[Shah (film)|Shah]]'' was released in Pakistan on 14 August 2015. The film chronicles Hussain Shah's poverty stricken childhood, his rise to fame as the Asian Boxing Champion and Olympic Bronze Medalist, his subsequent return to poverty and finally his migration to Japan to coach Japanese boxers. The movie is directed and written by [[Adnan Sarwar]] with music by Adnan Sarwar and Farhan Albert.\n\n==Olympic results==\n*1st round bye\n*Defeated {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Martin Amripallus]] 3-2\n*Defeated {{flagicon|ZAI}} [[Serge Kabongo]] 5-0\n*Defeated {{flagicon|HUN}} [[Zolt\u00e1n F\u00fczesy]] 3-2\n*Lost to {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Egerton Marcus]] 1-4\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sports.gov.pk/Awards/awards_boxing.htm Biography at Pakistan Sports Board]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shah, Hussain}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Sitara-i-Imtiaz]]\n[[Category:Pakistani expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:Sindhi people]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in boxing]]\n[[Category:Martial artists from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Asian Games medalists in boxing]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1986 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Pakistani male boxers]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1990 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games competitors for Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Lyari Town]]\n[[Category:Asian Games silver medalists for Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1986 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:South Asian Games gold medalists for Pakistan]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-boxing-bio-stub}}\n{{Pakistan-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pakistani boxer}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name           = Hussain Shah\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| realname       = Syed Hussain Shah\n| nickname       = \n| weight         = [[Middleweight#boxing|middleweight]]\n| height         = <!-- \"X ft Y in\" or \"X cm\" (conversions are automatic) -->\n| reach          = <!-- \"X in\" or \"X cm\" (conversions are automatic) -->\n| nationality    = [[Pakistan]]i\n| birth_name     = Syed Hussain Shah\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1964|08|14}}\n| birth_place    = [[Lyari]], [[Karachi]], Pakistan\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| style          = \n| total          = 4\n| wins           = 3\n| KO             = \n| losses         = 1\n| draws          = \n| no contests    = \n| website        = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Boxing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{PAK}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Boxing at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Seoul]] | [[Boxing at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Middleweight|Middleweight]]}}\n| show-medals    = yes\n| embed          = \n}}\n\n'''Syed Hussain Shah''' ({{lang-ur|\u0633\u064a\u062f \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646 \u0634\u0627\u0647}}) (born August 14, 1964) is a retired [[Pakistan]]i [[boxing|boxer]] from [[Lyari]], [[Karachi]] [[Pakistan]], who won the bronze medal in the Middleweight division (71\u201375&nbsp;kg) at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]] in [[Seoul]], South Korea. This was the country's first ever Olympic boxing medal.<ref name=\"news\">[http://www.thenews.com.pk/article-155105-Pakistans-Shah-Hussain-reaches-mens-judo-finals- Pakistan's Shah Hussain reaches men's judo final] 26 July 2014 Retrieved 26 July 2014</ref> He remains the only Pakistani sportsperson to win an individual medal at the [[Olympic Games]] in the last fifty-plus years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Must watch: An unsung Pakistani hero comes to life in film 'Shah'|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1191855|accessdate=17 February 2016|work=[[DAWN (newspaper)|DAWN]]|date=2 July 2015}}</ref> Only other Pakistani to ever win an individual Olympic medal is the wrestler [[Muhammad Bashir]], who won a bronze medal at the [[1960 Summer Olympics]].\n\n==Early life==\nShah was born in Lyari, Karachi. As a child Shah lived used to live on streets due to being homeless, he used to work as labor to earn money. Shah trained himself for boxing on streets using garbage bags as a replacement for [[punching bag]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/120097/hussain-shah-the-boxing-icon-who-won-olympic-medal-for-pakistan-in-1988/ |title=Hussain Shah \u2013 The boxing icon who won Olympic medal for Pakistan in 1988 |publisher=Daily Times |date=August 20, 2017 |website=dailytimes.com.pk |access-date=October 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShah won his first gold medal at [[1984 South Asian Games]] in [[Dhaka]], along with Asghar Ali, Ilyas Ahmed and Muhammad Yousaf.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sports.gov.pk/Participation/1st_SAF_Games.htm |title=I SAF Games |publisher=Pakistan Sports Board |website=sports.gov.pk |access-date=October 14, 2018}}</ref> At the [[1987 South Asian Games|1987 edition]] of the Games in [[Kolkata]], he was adjudged the 'best boxer'.<ref>{{cite newspaper |last1=Nair |first1=Avinash |title=Shah stops clean sweep |newspaper=The Indian Express |date=25 November 1987 |page=6}}</ref>\n\nAt the 1988 Olympics he shared the podium with [[Kenya]]'s [[Chris Sande]]. He was Pakistan's first boxer to win any medal in olympic boxing. In 1989, [[Lyari Town|Lyari]] born boxer received [[Sitara-i-Imtiaz]] medal from [[Government of Pakistan]].\n\nShah, who has also to his credit five gold in the South Asian Games history, remained the best boxer of Asia from 1980 to 1988, a rare prominence achieved by any Pakistani pugilist so far.\n\nHe later moved to Japan, where his son [[Shah Hussain Shah]] learned judo and went on to represent Pakistan at the international level.<ref>http://www.thenational.ae/sport/asian-games/shah-hussain-pakistans-young-japan-raised-judo-star-hopes-for-medal-repeat-at-asian-games</ref><ref>http://www.dawn.com/news/1122147</ref>\n\n==Films==\nA biopic called ''[[Shah (film)|Shah]]'' was released in Pakistan on 14 August 2015. The film chronicles Hussain Shah's poverty stricken childhood, his rise to fame as the Asian Boxing Champion and Olympic Bronze Medalist, his subsequent return to poverty and finally his migration to Japan to coach Japanese boxers. The movie is directed and written by [[Adnan Sarwar]] with music by Adnan Sarwar and Farhan Albert.\n\n==Olympic results==\n*1st round bye\n*Defeated {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Martin Amripallus]] 3-2\n*Defeated {{flagicon|ZAI}} [[Serge Kabongo]] 5-0\n*Defeated {{flagicon|HUN}} [[Zolt\u00e1n F\u00fczesy]] 3-2\n*Lost to {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Egerton Marcus]] 1-4\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sports.gov.pk/Awards/awards_boxing.htm Biography at Pakistan Sports Board]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shah, Hussain}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Sitara-i-Imtiaz]]\n[[Category:Pakistani expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:Sindhi people]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in boxing]]\n[[Category:Martial artists from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Asian Games medalists in boxing]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1986 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Pakistani male boxers]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1990 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games competitors for Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Lyari Town]]\n[[Category:Asian Games silver medalists for Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1986 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:South Asian Games gold medalists for Pakistan]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-boxing-bio-stub}}\n{{Pakistan-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zafarhamza93", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hussain_Shah"}
{"title_page": "Lists of World Heritage Sites", "text_new": "{{Short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n\n[[File:Welterbe.svg|thumb|150px|[[Logo]] of the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Committee]]]]\n\nThis is a list of the '''lists of World Heritage Sites'''. A '''[[World Heritage Site]]''' is a place that is listed by the [[UNESCO|United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization]] (UNESCO) as having special cultural or physical significance.\n\n==General lists==\n* [[Former UNESCO World Heritage Sites]]\n* [[List of World Heritage in Danger]]\n* [[List of World Heritage Sites by religion]]\n* [[List of World Heritage Sites by year of inscription]]\n* [[World Heritage Sites by country]]\n\n==Lists by continent==\n===Africa===\n* [[List of World Heritage Sites in Africa]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in the Arab States]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Botswana]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Egypt]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Ethiopia]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Kenya]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Madagascar]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Mauritania]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Morocco]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in South Africa]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Tanzania]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Tunisia]]\n\n=== Americas ===\n[[File:World_Heritage_Sites_in_the_Americas,_by_country.pdf|thumb|Proportional symbol map of World Heritage Sites in the Americas. Labeled with country name, total sites by country. Ring symbols indicate site type]]\n\n* [[List of World Heritage Sites in the Caribbean]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Antigua and Barbuda]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Barbados]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Cuba]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Dominica]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Dominican Republic]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Haiti]]\n** [[List of World Heritage Sites in Jamaica]]\n* [[Li